The creative delivery method for this creative will piggyback extra content. This extra content gets delivered when the creative is delivered and is acting in a fraudulent manner that includes, but is not limited to, cookie stuffing and impression fraud.
Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

column12: GhostCat-3PC: This malicious campaign utilizes advanced obfuscation and delivery patterns to evade signature-based detection. This malware evades conventional blockers in order to hijack users browser sessions for the purpose of delivering popups, redirects, and other phishing content. column12: This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the Google Play store without any user initiation. This content triggers a click action when the user has not yet clicked on any items causing the fraud to take place. The user is taken out of their current browser (or app) and forced into the Google Play store. Although not necessarily malicious, this behavior is unwanted and because of this, TMT is alerting on its presence.Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

Domain Does Not Exist: The flagged domain is not generating any content and is no longer connecting and executing during scanning. The Media Trust is not able to confirm the legitimacy of this domain. These types of domains often cause malicious redirects as they frequently expire and are associated with malicious content; bad actors take advantage of a domains one-time legitimacy and repurchase them to execute malicious campaigns.
To remediate this, please ensure this domain is removed from the delivery process and is no longer being called to and delivered.

This malware evades conventional blockers in order to hijack users browser sessions for the purpose of delivering popups, redirects, and other phishing content. Publisher visitors who fall victim to this malware may have malicious software installed on their device, including but not limited to Remote Access Trojans and adware.

This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the Google Play store without any user initiation. This content triggers a click action when the user has not yet clicked on any items causing the fraud to take place. The user is taken out of their current browser (or app) and forced into the Google Play store. Although not necessarily malicious, this behavior is unwanted and because of this, TMT is alerting on its presence.Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

column12: This malware campaign employs a sophisticated, multi-layered drive-by strategy to infect users. It deceives them into downloading malicious JavaScript under the guise of software updates such as urgent browser updates. Once the user downloads or installs these files, the embedded JavaScript executes, retrieving additional malicious components. These components establish command and control communication, ultimately delivering the final payload that includes Remote Access Trojans (RATs), information stealers, and more.

It deceives them into downloading malicious JavaScript under the guise of software updates such as urgent browser updates. Once the user downloads or installs these files, the embedded JavaScript executes, retrieving additional malicious components. These components establish command and control communication, ultimately delivering the final payload that includes Remote Access Trojans (RATs), information stealers, and more.

The creative delivery method for this creative will piggyback extra content. This extra content gets delivered when the creative is delivered and is acting in a fraudulent manner that includes, but is not limited to, cookie stuffing and impression fraud.

GhostCat-3PC: This malicious campaign utilizes advanced obfuscation and delivery patterns to evade signature-based detection. This malware evades conventional blockers in order to hijack users browser sessions for the purpose of delivering popups, redirects, and other phishing content. Publisher visitors who fall victim to this malware may have malicious software installed on their device, including but not limited to Remote Access Trojans and adware.

This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the iTunes store without any user initiation. This content triggers a click action when the user has not yet clicked on any items causing the fraud to take place. The user is taken out of their current browser (or app) and forced into iTunes. Although not necessarily malicious, this behavior is unwanted and because of this, TMT is alerting on its presence.Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

This malware campaign employs a sophisticated, multi-layered drive-by strategy to infect users. It deceives them into downloading malicious JavaScript under the guise of software updates such as urgent browser updates. Once the user downloads or installs these files, the embedded JavaScript executes, retrieving additional malicious components. These components establish command and control communication, ultimately delivering the final payload that includes Remote Access Trojans (RATs), information stealers, and more.

Phishing Domain: This domain delivers malicious popups and other phishing content such as fake surveys, gift card prizes, and fraudulent offers designed to trick users into disclosing personal information or downloading malware onto their device. These deceptive tactics are designed to exploit unsuspecting individuals, leading to potential financial loss, identity theft, and compromised security.

This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the iTunes store without any user initiation. This content triggers a click action when the user has not yet clicked on any items causing the fraud to take place. The user is taken out of their current browser (or app) and forced into iTunes. Although not necessarily malicious, this behavior is unwanted and because of this, TMT is alerting on its presence.Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

GhostCat-3PC: This malicious campaign utilizes advanced obfuscation and delivery patterns to evade signature-based detection. This malware evades conventional blockers in order to hijack users browser sessions for the purpose of delivering popups, redirects, and other phishing content. Publisher visitors who fall victim to this malware may have malicious software installed on their device, including but not limited to Remote Access Trojans and adware.

This malware campaign employs a sophisticated, multi-layered drive-by strategy to infect users. It deceives them into downloading malicious JavaScript under the guise of software updates such as urgent browser updates. Once the user downloads or installs these files, the embedded JavaScript executes, retrieving additional malicious components. These components establish command and control communication, ultimately delivering the final payload that includes Remote Access Trojans (RATs), information stealers, and more.

Domain Does Not Exist: The flagged domain is not generating any content and is no longer connecting and executing during scanning. The Media Trust is not able to confirm the legitimacy of this domain. These types of domains often cause malicious redirects as they frequently expire and are associated with malicious content; bad actors take advantage of a domains one-time legitimacy and repurchase them to execute malicious campaigns.
To remediate this, please ensure this domain is removed from the delivery process and is no longer being called to and delivered.

The creative delivery method for this creative will piggyback extra content. This extra content gets delivered when the creative is delivered and is acting in a fraudulent manner that includes, but is not limited to, cookie stuffing and impression fraud.
Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.
This content is a phishing/credential theft scam enticing users to enter personal information that is then leveraged in the future to harm the consumer or the corporate entity the consumer works for.

GhostCat-3PC: This malicious campaign utilizes advanced obfuscation and delivery patterns to evade signature-based detection. This malware evades conventional blockers in order to hijack users browser sessions for the purpose of delivering popups, redirects, and other phishing content. Publisher visitors who fall victim to this malware may have malicious software installed on their device, including but not limited to Remote Access Trojans and adware.

This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the Google Play store without any user initiation. This content triggers a click action when the user has not yet clicked on any items causing the fraud to take place. The user is taken out of their current browser (or app) and forced into the Google Play store. Although not necessarily malicious, this behavior is unwanted and because of this, TMT is alerting on its presence.Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

column12: This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the iTunes store without any user initiation. column12: This malware campaign employs a sophisticated, multi-layered drive-by strategy to infect users. It deceives them into downloading malicious JavaScript under the guise of software updates such as urgent browser updates. Once the user downloads or installs these files, the embedded JavaScript executes, retrieving additional malicious components. These components establish command and control communication, ultimately delivering the final payload that includes Remote Access Trojans (RATs), information stealers, and more.

column12:
Domain Does Not Exist: The flagged domain is not generating any content and is no longer connecting and executing during scanning. The Media Trust is not able to confirm the legitimacy of this domain. These types of domains often cause malicious redirects as they frequently expire and are associated with malicious content; bad actors take advantage of a domains one-time legitimacy and repurchase them to execute malicious campaigns.
To remediate this, please ensure this domain is removed from the delivery process and is no longer being called to and delivered.

Domain Does Not Exist: The flagged domain is not generating any content and is no longer connecting and executing during scanning. The Media Trust is not able to confirm the legitimacy of this domain. These types of domains often cause malicious redirects as they frequently expire and are associated with malicious content; bad actors take advantage of a domains one-time legitimacy and repurchase them to execute malicious campaigns.
To remediate this, please ensure this domain is removed from the delivery process and is no longer being called to and delivered.

column12: This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the Google Play store without any user initiation. This content triggers a click action when the user has not yet clicked on any items causing the fraud to take place. The user is taken out of their current browser (or app) and forced into the Google Play store. Although not necessarily malicious, this behavior is unwanted and because of this, TMT is alerting on its presence.Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

Domain Does Not Exist: The flagged domain is not generating any content and is no longer connecting and executing during scanning. The Media Trust is not able to confirm the legitimacy of this domain. These types of domains often cause malicious redirects as they frequently expire and are associated with malicious content; bad actors take advantage of a domains one-time legitimacy and repurchase them to execute malicious campaigns.
To remediate this, please ensure this domain is removed from the delivery process and is no longer being called to and delivered.

column12: Phishing Domain: This domain delivers malicious popups and other phishing content such as fake surveys, gift card prizes, and fraudulent offers designed to trick users into disclosing personal information or downloading malware onto their device. These deceptive tactics are designed to exploit unsuspecting individuals, leading to potential financial loss, identity theft, and compromised security.

This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the iTunes store without any user initiation. This content triggers a click action when the user has not yet clicked on any items causing the fraud to take place. The user is taken out of their current browser (or app) and forced into iTunes. Although not necessarily malicious, this behavior is unwanted and because of this, TMT is alerting on its presence.Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

It deceives them into downloading malicious JavaScript under the guise of software updates such as urgent browser updates. These components establish command and control communication, ultimately delivering the final payload that includes Remote Access Trojans (RATs), information stealers, and more.

This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the iTunes store without any user initiation. column12: This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the iTunes store without any user initiation. This content triggers a click action when the user has not yet clicked on any items causing the fraud to take place. The user is taken out of their current browser (or app) and forced into iTunes. Although not necessarily malicious, this behavior is unwanted and because of this, TMT is alerting on its presence.Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

Domain Does Not Exist: The flagged domain is not generating any content and is no longer connecting and executing during scanning. The Media Trust is not able to confirm the legitimacy of this domain. These types of domains often cause malicious redirects as they frequently expire and are associated with malicious content; bad actors take advantage of a domains one-time legitimacy and repurchase them to execute malicious campaigns.
To remediate this, please ensure this domain is removed from the delivery process and is no longer being called to and delivered.

StringRipper-3PC: This highly advanced malvertising campaign exploits legitimate ad demand through sophisticated obfuscation and a multi-stage evasion strategy. It employs techniques such as delayed execution, environment checks, heavy obfuscation, DOM and iframe manipulation, global function overrides, fingerprinting, and dynamic code execution. By mimicking legitimate user interactions with randomized timing and dynamic function creation, it successfully bypasses traditional security systems. Domain Does Not Exist: The flagged domain is not generating any content and is no longer connecting and executing during scanning. The Media Trust is not able to confirm the legitimacy of this domain. These types of domains often cause malicious redirects as they frequently expire and are associated with malicious content; bad actors take advantage of a domains one-time legitimacy and repurchase them to execute malicious campaigns.
To remediate this, please ensure this domain is removed from the delivery process and is no longer being called to and delivered.

column14: Suspicious (Multiple indicators match known overt incidents but no overt actions detected.)

column12: This content has been seen to trigger click fraud activity in ad delivery as well as auto redirect users to the iTunes store without any user initiation. This content triggers a click action when the user has not yet clicked on any items causing the fraud to take place. The user is taken out of their current browser (or app) and forced into iTunes. Although not necessarily malicious, this behavior is unwanted and because of this, TMT is alerting on its presence.Often times the fix is as simple as removing the click URL from the 1x1 iframe where an impression URL is typically located.

The creative delivery method for this creative will piggyback extra content. This extra content gets delivered when the creative is delivered and is acting in a fraudulent manner that includes, but is not limited to, cookie stuffing and impression fraud.
